Team 6459 is back with an exciting offseason project—meet Leblebi ! While the full design is still in progress, we’re thrilled to share some of the foundational work we’ve completed so far.

  • We’re thrilled to welcome a wave of new members to our team this offseason! Our top priority is helping them get involved and feel like an integral part of the crew from day one
  • After our success at the 2024 Cezeri Robot Ligi Ümraniye Robotik Yarışları we’re determined to keep the momentum going by building more and pushing our capabilities further!
  • Leblebi, is set to make its on-field debut at the Cezeri Robot Ligi Bahçelievler Off-Season! It will join our competition bot, Arnica
    *, as we prepare for an exciting event showcasing both of the robots
  • Our ultimate goal is to field two robots while ensuring every team member gets hands-on experience and a chance to grow their skills.

CAD
The CAD for Leblebi is kinda complete, with just the intake, and a few finer details left to finalize.

PHOTO-2024-12-08-16-47-041038×856 181 KB

PHOTO-2024-12-08-16-47-051164×957 194 KB

  • Shooter with 3D-Printed Flywheels
  • Polycarbonate Rollers (if could provided from local sellers)
  • Herringbone Gear for shooter angles

Oh and some real-life updates for the robot!:

Leblebi Updates #1

We’ve made some exciting strides and wanted to loop everyone in on the latest developments.

Shooter Flywheels

Our team has just finished 3D printing the shooter flywheels, and we’re planning to wrap them with CatTongue grip tape for that extra “stick” to help us control the game pieces. Here is the 3D-printed flywheels:

SHOOTER FOTO KIRPILMIS1920×1710 165 KB

Herringbone Gear

Plus, we will be using a mini version of our herringbone gear because who doesn’t love gear geometry?

Herringbone Foto1200×1600 249 KB

Precision Shooter Adjustments

But here’s the real kicker: We’re stepping up our precision game by incorporating a Kraken X60’s built-in encoder for angle adjustments on the shooter. This is a new venture for our team, and we’re pretty stoked to see how it affects our accuracy. It’s all about learning, trying new things, and pushing our capabilities just a bit further each day. (Or maybe just using CANcoders )

Leblebi Updates #2

Our team has been testing intake feeder rollers and experimenting with angle adjustments, and we’re excited to share the results with you!

Intake Feeder Roller

We’ve just mounted our new polycarbonate intake rollers, which have a 50mm radius and 2mm width and are wrapped in CatTongue grip tape for maximum grip.

This is a big milestone for our intake mechanism, and we’re already looking at ways to fine-tune the setup for even better performance.

This marks an exciting step forward in perfecting Leblebi’s intake system. We’re already brainstorming minor adjustments to make it even more reliable.

Angle Adjustment Testing

In addition to the rollers, we’ve been working on the shooter’s angle adjustment mechanism and the early results are promising! Check out a quick look at the process:

Leblebi Updates #3

We’re back with exciting progress on Leblebi as we fine-tune its components for peak performance on the field!

Updated Flywheel

The flywheel has been wrapped with CatTongue grip tape to improve both grip and accuracy.

flywheel cattounge1920×1440 121 KB

Updated Feeder Roller

We’ve introduced a new feeder roller that’s identical to the intake rollers. It’s a polycarbonate roller with a 50mm radius and 2mm width, wrapped in CatTongue grip tape for improved handling of game pieces.

feeder fotograf1920×2560 187 KB

What’s Next?

We’re planning to kick off the electronics work in just two days, and the entire team is buzzing with excitement to bring Leblebi’s systems to life.

Leblebi Updates #4

The assembly process for Leblebi is nearly complete! Here’s a quick rundown of what we’ve accomplished so far:

Herringbone Gear Assembly

The herringbone gear system has been fully assembled and mounted.

herringbone assembly foto 11920×1440 340 KB

Shooter Assembly

The shooter has been assembled and mounted, complete with the flywheel wrapped in CatTongue grip tape for added grip and accuracy.
Close-up of the belt setup:

shooter assembly #31920×1440 230 KB

Close-up of the “Flywheel mounting supports”:

shooter assembly #21920×1440 304 KB

Close-up of the shaft collars with the supports
shooter assembly # 11920×2560 371 KB

Only the Intake Left to Assemble

The final piece is the intake system. Once that’s done, Leblebi will be fully assembled.

We’ll begin testing Leblebi as soon as the electronics are complete (probably before the intake assembly) and will share footage of it in action. Stay tuned for more updates and progress as we approach competition day!

We’d love to hear your thoughts, feedback, or any questions you might have about our progress so far. Don’t hesitate to comment or share suggestions—we’re always open to new ideas!

Leblebi Updates #5

We’re thrilled to announce that Leblebi is now fully assembled. This marks a huge milestone in our build process as we finalize the robot’s core components.

The newly completed intake system has been rigorously tested and performs flawlessly, smoothly handling game pieces with precision and efficiency. Check out the video below to see Leblebi’s intake in action:

With the assembly complete, our focus now shifts to fine-tuning and testing all systems to ensure top performance at the Off-Season event.
We’d love to hear your feedback or answer any questions about the build process or the intake’s functionality. Let us know your thoughts in the comments! Stay tuned for more updates as we get closer to competition day!

Leblebi Updates #7: Final Prep Before the Event!

The big day is almost here, and Leblebi is ready to roll! Here’s what we’ve been working on:

  • Driver practice: With plenty of game pieces set up on the practice field, our drivers are getting lots of time to refine their skills.

    IMG_23051920×1440 308 KB

  • Electronics in Action: Leblebi’s electronics system has been fully integrated and tested, ensuring all systems are functioning properly.
    (nobody says no to a photo where the robot can see the bottom of it )

    robot alt leblebi1920×2560 603 KB

  • Cycle testing: We’ve begun testing full cycles to ensure smooth and efficient(maybe?)
    operation


  • Bug fixes and upgrades: A few software tweaks were made

  • And we’ve also upgraded Arnica’s wheels from Colson wheels to billet wheels for improved durability and performance on the field.

Let’s hope we bring home the win! Stay tuned for updates post-match, and thank you for being part of Leblebi’s journey!

Oh and lastly, a video of our mentor figuring out the momentary control:

Leblebi Updates #8: Wrapping Up an Incredible Season!

IMG_23941920×1440 358 KB

IMG_23921920×1440 377 KB

IMG_23691920×1440 282 KB

With only 3 days left in the season, we’re here with our final update! The Cezeri Başakşehir Off-Season event was an amazing experience for us. Here are some highlights from our journey:

Autons with Leblebi

Leblebi’s autonomous systems performed flawlessly during the event. In fact, together with Arnica, we managed to achieve a 10-note auton!



Challenges and Lessons Learned

Of course, not everything went perfectly, a few not working autonomous periods led to us burning out a Neo 550. And in the final match, Leblebi’s intake roller broke because of a hard contact! (But you know, it was the last match and the new season is just 3 days away so we did not care about it that much)


IMG_24331920×2560 291 KB

IMG_24351920×2560 333 KB

Team Achievements and Awards

Both of our teams achieved incredible success at the event:

  • 6459 AG Robotik and 9999 Robopiece won the Winner Award as event champions!
  • 6459 AG Robotik won the Innovation in Control Award
  • 9999 Robopiece won the Autonomous Award

Leblebi’s Cycles

Want to see some of Leblebi’s on-field performance? Check out a few of its cycles:

We want to thank all our mentors, teammates, and supporters for being with us throughout this season.

673aa33f-3781-4938-93bf-c3632f40a0a01536×2048 484 KB


Now, it’s time to start preparing for the next season. See you soon!
